title: 30 Minute Spicy Red Fish Stew
summary: You can never have too many main course recipes, so give 30 Minute Spicy Red Fish Stew a try. This recipe makes 1 servings with 949 calories, 73g of protein, and 37g of fat each. For $10.27 per serving, this recipe covers 60% of your daily requirements of vitamins and minerals. 17 people have tried and liked this recipe. It will be a hit at your Autumn event. From preparation to the plate, this recipe takes roughly 45 minutes. Head to the store and pick up minute spicy fish stew, pepper flakes, cilantro, and a few other things to make it today. To use up the lemon zest you could follow this main course with the Orange Marmalade Cookies with Orange Zest Icing as a dessert. It is a good option if you're following a pescatarian diet. All things considered, we decided this recipe deserves a spoonacular score of 97%. This score is amazing. Try 30-Minute Spicy Pork and Sweet Potato Stew, Spicy fish stew, and 5-Minute Roasted Red Pepper Dip for similar recipes.

winePairing.pairingText: Fish works really well with Pinot Grigio, Gruener Veltliner, and Pinot Noir. Fish is as diverse as wine, so it's hard to pick wines that go with every fish. A crisp white wine, such as a pinot grigio or Grüner Veltliner, will suit any delicately flavored white fish. Meaty, strongly flavored fish such as salmon and tuna can even handle a light red wine, such as a pinot noir. One wine you could try is La Fiera Pinot Grigio. It has 4 out of 5 stars and a bottle costs about 7 dollars.

productMatches.title: La Fiera Pinot Grigio
productMatches.description: This wine has a light straw color with green tints. It has a light floral and fruity bouquet featuring apples and pears. The palate is bright, fresh and dry showing nice balance and a lingering acidity perfect for a variety of lighter cuisine.Blend: 100% Pinot Grigio

instructions: (For best results with this recipe, use a small frying pan with high sides so the fish pieces will be surrounded by liquid when you add them.  I used an 8 inch pan.)Heat olive oil in small frying pan, add chopped red onion or shallot and saute over medium heat about 3-4 minutes, until onions are soft and starting to brown.  Add chopped red bell peppers, diced tomatoes with juice, finely minced fresh garlic, and red pepper flakes.  Let mixture simmer 10 minutes over medium-low heat, until garlic is cooked and flavors are well-blended.While stew mixture simmers, zest and juice the lemon, and chop the cilantro.   Cut fish fillets into 1 inch pieces and blot dry with paper towel if needed.Add lemon zest, lemon juice, and 1/4 cup chopped cilantro to stew mixture, then add fish pieces and gently stir to combine.  Let stew simmer 5-7 minutes or until fish is barely turning opaque and some liquid from the fish is being released into the stew.  Stir again, season to taste with salt and fresh ground black pepper and serve hot, with additional chopped cilantro for garnish if desired.

steps.step: (For best results with this recipe, use a small frying pan with high sides so the fish pieces will be surrounded by liquid when you add them.  I used an 8 inch pan.)
Heat olive oil in small frying pan, add chopped red onion or shallot and saute over medium heat about 3-4 minutes, until onions are soft and starting to brown.
Add chopped red bell peppers, diced tomatoes with juice, finely minced fresh garlic, and red pepper flakes.
Let mixture simmer 10 minutes over medium-low heat, until garlic is cooked and flavors are well-blended.While stew mixture simmers, zest and juice the lemon, and chop the cilantro.
Cut fish fillets into 1 inch pieces and blot dry with paper towel if needed.
Add lemon zest, lemon juice, and 1/4 cup chopped cilantro to stew mixture, then add fish pieces and gently stir to combine.

Let stew simmer 5-7 minutes or until fish is barely turning opaque and some liquid from the fish is being released into the stew.  Stir again, season to taste with salt and fresh ground black pepper and serve hot, with additional chopped cilantro for garnish if desired.
